The simple rule for writing small number is to precisely count
the number of digit(s) after decimal point (.) e.g.
<p>
5 tenths = 0.5 (<strong>1 digit</strong>)
<br>
5 hundredths = 0.05 (<strong>2 digits</strong>)
<br>
5 thousandths = 0.005 (<strong>3 digits</strong>)
<br>
5 ten thousandths = 0.0005 (<strong>4 digits</strong>)
<br>
5 hundred thousandths = 0.00005 (<strong>5 digits</strong>)
<br>
5 thousand thousandths or 5 millionths = 0.000005 (<strong>6 digits</strong>)
<div class="container-fluid">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col border-right border-danger">
    <b>Example 1</b>
    <br>
    Write the following as decimal fractions; 
    <br>
    (i) 15 thousandths
    <br>
    (ii) <sup>465</sup>&frasl;<sub>100000</sub>
    <br> 
    (iii) 150 millionths
    <br> 
    (iv) <sup>200</sup>&frasl;<sub>10000</sub>
    </div>
    <div class="col">
    <b>Solution</b>
    <br>
    (i)	15 thousandths = 15 x 1 thousandths = 15 x 0.001 =><strong> 0.015</strong>
    <br>
    (ii) <sup>456</sup>&frasl;<sub>100000</sub> = <strong>0.00465</strong>
    <br>
    (iii)	150 millionths = 150 x 0.000001 =><strong> 0.00015</strong>
    <br>
    (iv)<sup>200</sup>&frasl;<sub>10000</sub> = 0.0200 => <strong>0.02</strong>
    <br>
    </div>
  </div>
  </div>
<br>
<h6>
